<DOC><DOCNO> AP880401-0195 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 1807EST</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     04-01 0424</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0438</SECOND><HEAD>April Rain Turns To Snow Over The Southern Plains</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   A storm spread snow up to 10 inches of snow from the southernRockies to the southern Plains on Friday, and heavy rain ahead ofthe storm raised a threat of flooding.   Snow fell over the southeastern third of Colorado, thenortheastern half of New Mexico, the Texas Panhandle, the OklahomaPanhandle and western Kansas.   There were reports of 10 inches of snow over sections of theTexas Panhandle and 6 inches of snow at Ulysses, Kan., the NationalWeather Service said.   In Oklahoma, the range was from 5 inches near Boise City to 10inches near Guymon. Amounts in Colorado were mostly around 3 inchesor less.   The snow closed some highways in the Texas and Oklahomapanhandles.   Ahead of the snow, rain and thunderstorms extended from theremainder of Kansas and Oklahoma into eastern Texas, producingmarble-size hail in Oklahoma. Ground in the southern half of thePlains was already saturated and flash flood watches were postedover northeastern and central Oklahoma and the southeastern quarterof Kansas.   The Caney River was expected to crest during the night atBartlesville, Okla., at about 3 feet above flood stage. The NeoshoRiver was expected to crest about 4 feet above flood stage Sundayevening at Commerce, Okla., and Oswego, Kan.   Showers extended across northeastern Texas, the lower two-thirdsof the Mississippi Valley, the Ohio Valley, the Tennessee Valley,eastern Mississippi, Alabama, western Georgia, northernPennsylvania and southern New York state.   Elsewhere, rain continued over the northern Oregon coast.   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 26degrees at Yellowstone National Park, Wyo., to 85 degrees atKingsville, Texas. The early morning low for the nation was zero atYellowstone National Park.   For Saturday, rain and occasional thunderstorms were forecastfrom New Jersey across Pennsylvania, the Ohio Valley and theTennessee Valley, from the northwestern half of Georgia across theFlorida Panhandle, Alabama, Mississippi and southeastern Louisiana,and from Iowa across Missouri, northern Arkansas, the east-centralPlains, Illinois, southern Wisconsin and Lower Michigan. Scatteredrain was forecast over the northern Pacific Coast.   Highs in the 40s and 50s were predicted over New England, theGreat Lakes, the upper Mississippi Valley, the central Plains,Oklahoma, the Texas Panhandle and the southern Rockies, as well asthe Pacific Northwest; in the 80s over the Florida Peninsula,southern Texas, central California and the desert Southwest, and inthe 60s and 70s over the remainder of the nation.</TEXT></DOC>